Creating a practical example is an excellent way to illustrate the concepts you've covered. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you set up a simple form that accepts user input and saves it to a local storage:

**Example: Simple Form with Local Storage**

For this example, we'll use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. We'll create a form that accepts a user's name, email, and message, and then saves this data to local storage.

**Step 1: Create the HTML Structure**

Create an HTML file (e.g., `index.html`) and add the following code:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Simple Form with Local Storage</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Simple Form with Local Storage</h1>
    <form id="user-form">
        <label for="name">Name:</label>
        <input type="text" id="name" name="name"><br><br>
        <label for="email">Email:</label>
        <input type="email" id="email" name="email"><br><br>
        <label for="message">Message:</label>
        <textarea id="message" name="message"></textarea><br><br>
        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
    <div id="result"></div>

    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```
This code creates a basic form with input fields for name, email, and message, as well as a submit button.

**Step 2: Add CSS Styling (Optional)**

Create a CSS file (e.g., `styles.css`) and add the following code:
```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

#user-form {
    width: 50%;
    margin: 40px auto;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-radius: 10px;
    box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
}

label {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
}

input, textarea {
    width: 100%;
    padding: 10px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
}

button[type="submit"] {
    background-color: #4CAF50;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 5px;
    cursor: pointer;
}

button[type="submit"]:hover {
    background-color: #3e8e41;
}
```
This code adds basic styling to the form, but feel free to customize it as you see fit.

**Step 3: Add JavaScript Code**

Create a JavaScript file (e.g., `script.js`) and add the following code:
```javascript
// Get the form element
const form = document.getElementById('user-form');

// Add an event listener to the form
form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    // Get the input values
    const name = document.getElementById('name').value;
    const email = document.getElementById('email').value;
    const message = document.getElementById('message').value;

    // Save the data to local storage
    localStorage.setItem('user-data', JSON.stringify({
        name,
        email,
        message
    }));

    // Display a success message
    const result = document.getElementById('result');
    result.innerHTML = 'Data saved successfully!';
});

// Load the saved data from local storage
const storedData = localStorage.getItem('user-data');
if (storedData) {
    const userData = JSON.parse(storedData);
    document.getElementById('result').innerHTML = `Name: ${userData.name}<br>Email: ${userData.email}<br>Message: ${userData.message}`;
}
```
This code adds an event listener to the form, which saves the input values to local storage when the form is submitted. It also loads the saved data from local storage and displays it on the page.

**Step 4: Test the Example**

Open the `index.html` file in a web browser and fill out the form. Submit the form to save the data to local storage. Then, reload the page to see the saved data displayed on the page.

